    slug: "digital-marketing-strategy-small-business-2025",
    title: "Digital Marketing Strategy for Small Businesses in 2025: What Actually Works",
    excerpt: "A practical guide to digital marketing for SMEs in 2025: from Google My Business and SEO to email automation and social media — ranked by ROI.",
    category: "Маркетинг",
    tags: ["Marketing", "SEO", "Email Marketing", "Social Media", "SMB"],
    date: "2026-05-01",
    readTime: 9,
    author: "Oleksiy Kovalenko",
    featured: false,
    emoji: "📣",
    color: "from-rose-500 to-pink-600",
    content: [],
    contentEn: [
      "Most small businesses make the same mistake: they try every marketing channel at once and end up doing none of them well. In 2025, the winning formula is doing 2–3 channels exceptionally well, rather than 10 channels poorly. Here's a ranked breakdown by ROI to help you prioritise.",
      "**1. Google My Business (Highest ROI, Free)**\n\nIf your business has a physical location or serves a local area, Google My Business (now called Google Business Profile) is the single highest-ROI marketing action you can take. It's free, takes 30 minutes to set up, and can send you dozens of customers per month.\n\nKey actions:\n1. Verify your listing and fill in every field (hours, photos, services)\n2. Collect reviews — email every happy customer\n3. Post weekly updates (special offers, new products)\n4. Respond to all reviews within 24 hours\n\nBusinesses with 50+ reviews and complete profiles average 7× more profile visits than those with minimal information.",
      "**2. SEO — Compounding Returns**\n\nUnlike paid ads, every SEO improvement compounds over time. A blog post you write today can drive traffic for years. The key is focusing on intent: what is your customer searching for when they need your product?\n\nFor small businesses, local SEO is most powerful:\n- Target '[service] [city]' keywords (e.g., 'wedding photographer Kyiv')\n- Write 5–10 deep blog articles answering your customers' top questions\n- Get listed in local directories (Yelp, TripAdvisor, niche directories)\n- Build internal links between your service pages and blog posts\n\nRealistic timeline: 3–6 months to see significant organic traffic from new content.",
      "**3. Email Marketing — Best Retention Tool**\n\nEmail remains the highest-converting channel for repeat business. Average ROI: £36 for every £1 spent. The key is building your list actively and segmenting it intelligently.\n\nPractical setup in 2025:\n1. Use Mailchimp (free up to 500 contacts) or Brevo\n2. Offer a lead magnet to grow your list (free guide, discount, checklist)\n3. Set up a 3–5 email welcome sequence for new subscribers\n4. Send a monthly newsletter with value (tips, case studies, updates) — not just promotions\n5. Segment by purchase history or interest to personalise offers",
      "**4. Social Media — Choose One Platform**\n\nThe biggest social media mistake: trying to post on Instagram, Facebook, TikTok, and LinkedIn simultaneously. Unless you have a dedicated content team, pick the one platform your customers use most and dominate it.\n\nPlatform selection guide:\n- B2C physical products / lifestyle: Instagram or TikTok\n- B2B services / professional services: LinkedIn\n- Local services: Facebook (still #1 for local community engagement)\n- Restaurants / food / events: Instagram Stories + TikTok\n\nPost 3–4 times per week consistently for 3 months before evaluating results.",
      "**What to do this week**\n\n1. Audit your Google Business Profile — is it 100% complete?\n2. Check your top 5 website pages in Google Search Console — what queries are you ranking for?\n3. Set up a simple email capture on your website if you don't have one\n4. Pick one social platform and plan content for the next 4 weeks\n\nThe Codeworth team builds marketing-optimised websites that turn visitors into enquiries. If you want to understand which channels are working for your business specifically, start with a free 30-minute consultation.",
    ],
