    contentEn: [
      "When you are buying a website, three technical terms come up repeatedly: domain, SSL, and hosting. Most web agencies treat these as obvious, but they are genuinely confusing if you have not dealt with them before. Here is what each one actually means, how they work together, and what you should expect to pay for them in 2025.",
      "**Domain Name: Your Website Address**\n\nA domain name (e.g., yourbusiness.co.uk or yourbusiness.com) is the human-readable address people type to reach your website. You do not own a domain outright - you register it for a period (typically 1-10 years) and renew it annually.\n\nCosts in the UK:\n- .co.uk: 5-12 GBP/year\n- .com: 10-15 GBP/year\n- .uk: 5-10 GBP/year\n\nKey advice: register your domain yourself via a registrar like 123-reg, Namecheap or GoDaddy - never let an agency register it on your behalf without transferring control to you. Your domain is your business address; you must own the account.\n\nChoose .co.uk for a UK-focused business (Google UK search prefers it), .com if you are targeting international customers, or both and redirect one to the other.",
      "**SSL Certificate: The Padlock in the Browser Bar**\n\nSSL encrypts data between your website and visitors browsers. The visible sign is https:// in the URL and a padlock icon. Without it, browsers display Not Secure warnings - immediately damaging trust.\n\nSince 2014, Google has used HTTPS as a positive ranking signal. Since 2018, Chrome actively flags HTTP sites as insecure. In 2025, there is no valid reason for a business website to be without SSL.\n\nCost: free. Services like Let's Encrypt provide free SSL certificates, and most modern hosting platforms (Vercel, Netlify, Cloudflare) issue and renew them automatically. If an agency tries to charge you separately for SSL, ask why it is not included.\n\nFor e-commerce or any site processing payments, a standard DV (Domain Validated) SSL is sufficient. EV (Extended Validation) certificates - the ones that show your company name - are rarely worth the extra cost for small businesses.",
      "**Web Hosting: Where Your Website Lives**\n\nHosting is the server that stores your website files and delivers them to visitors. The type of hosting you need depends on your website's size, traffic, and technology.\n\nShared hosting (3-10 GBP/month): Multiple websites on one server. Fine for small brochure sites with low traffic. Limitation: slow during traffic spikes, limited configuration.\n\nManaged cloud hosting (15-50 GBP/month): Your site on cloud infrastructure with management handled by the provider. Best for most business websites in 2025. Platforms: Vercel (ideal for Next.js), Netlify, WP Engine.\n\nVPS / Dedicated server (30-200 GBP/month): Full control of a virtual or physical server. Needed only for large e-commerce, high-traffic sites, or custom server requirements.\n\nFor a Next.js website, Vercel is the natural choice - it is the company that created Next.js, deployment is instant, SSL is automatic, and the free tier handles most small business traffic levels.",
      "**Common Mistakes Business Owners Make**\n\n1. Letting the agency keep control of your domain. Always register in your own name, your own account.\n2. Paying for premium hosting when basic cloud hosting handles your traffic. Most small business sites receive under 10,000 visits/month - Vercel free tier is more than sufficient.\n3. Not renewing the domain on time. Set auto-renewal on day one, using a personal email you will always have access to.\n4. Confusing hosting and domain providers. You can buy a domain from Namecheap and host on Vercel - they do not have to be the same company.\n5. Choosing UK-based hosting for SEO reasons. Server location matters far less than CDN coverage.",
      "**Conclusion: What You Should Expect to Pay**\n\nFor a standard business website in 2025: domain (10-15 GBP/year) + hosting on Vercel free tier (0 GBP) or paid Pro plan (20 GBP/month) = under 30 GBP/month total. SSL is included at no additional cost. Any quote that adds separate charges for SSL or implies hosting is expensive for a small site warrants scrutiny. Codeworth delivers every project with the domain registered in your name, SSL configured automatically, and hosting on Vercel - full ownership from day one.",
    ],
