    slug: "ml-fraud-detection-guide",
    title: "Real-time Fraud Detection with ML: Architecture and Results",
    excerpt: "How to build a production-grade ML fraud detection system that processes 10,000+ transactions per second with sub-50ms latency and 99.1% accuracy.",
    author: "Oleksiy Kovalenko",
    category: "AI та Автоматизація",
    tags: ["ML", "Fraud Detection", "FinTech", "Real-time", "Anomaly Detection"],
    date: "2026-05-02",
    readTime: 11,
    emoji: "🛡️",
    color: "from-red-600 to-rose-800",
    featured: false,
    content: [],
    contentEn: [
      "**Why Rule-Based Fraud Detection Fails at Scale**\n\nTraditional rule-based systems flag transactions based on fixed thresholds: amount > £5,000, foreign IP, new device. The problem: fraudsters learn the rules. A sophisticated attacker splits a £10,000 transfer into 9 transactions of £1,100 each — every rule passes. Meanwhile, your rules are blocking 3% of legitimate transactions, frustrating real customers.\n\nThe UK financial sector loses over £1.2 billion annually to fraud (UK Finance, 2024). FCA-regulated firms face direct liability when controls are demonstrably inadequate. ML-based detection doesn't replace compliance requirements — it makes them achievable at modern transaction volumes.",
      "**How ML Fraud Detection Works**\n\nAn ML fraud system combines several model types working in parallel:\n\n**Anomaly Detection (Unsupervised)** — Isolation Forest or Autoencoder models learn what 'normal' looks like for each customer. A transaction that deviates significantly from the customer's behavioural baseline gets flagged regardless of absolute amount.\n\n**Binary Classification (Supervised)** — XGBoost or LightGBM trained on labelled fraud/non-fraud data. Features include: velocity (5 transactions in 2 minutes), geolocation delta (London → Lagos in 3 hours), device fingerprint, merchant category, time-of-day patterns.\n\n**Graph Neural Networks** — Detect fraud rings by mapping relationships between accounts, devices, and IP addresses. A single fraudster controlling 40 synthetic accounts leaves a detectable network signature.\n\n**Real-time Feature Store** — All three models need features computed in <5ms. This requires a streaming feature store (Redis + Apache Flink) that maintains rolling aggregates: last 1h/24h/7d spend by merchant category, velocity per card, etc.",
      "**Architecture for 10,000 TPS**\n\nThe GuardAI system we built for an FCA-regulated payment processor handles 10,000+ transactions per second:\n\n```\nTransaction Event → Kafka Topic (3ms)\n    ↓\nFlink Stream Processor → Feature Computation (8ms)\n    ↓\nModel Ensemble (XGBoost + Isolation Forest) → Score (12ms)\n    ↓\nDecision Engine → Block / Review / Allow (5ms)\n    ↓\nCase Management System + Real-time Alerts\n```\n\nTotal latency: 28ms p50, 47ms p99. The Kafka buffer absorbs traffic spikes (Black Friday peaks at 3x baseline). Models are deployed via MLflow with A/B traffic splitting — new model versions receive 5% traffic before full rollout.\n\nInfrastructure: 6× c5.2xlarge (model serving), 3× r5.4xlarge (feature store), managed Kafka on AWS MSK. Monthly infrastructure cost: £4,200.",
      "**Handling Class Imbalance**\n\nFraud rates in production are typically 0.1-0.3%. Training a model on raw data means 99.7% of examples are 'not fraud' — the model learns to always predict 'not fraud' and achieves 99.7% accuracy while being completely useless.\n\nSolution: SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique) combined with cost-sensitive learning. We assign a misclassification cost of £150 per missed fraud (average transaction value) vs £2 per false positive (manual review cost). The model optimises for business cost, not raw accuracy.\n\nMetrics that matter: Precision-Recall curve, not ROC-AUC. At 0.5% FPR (false positive rate), our model achieves 94.3% recall — meaning we catch 94 out of every 100 fraud cases while blocking only 1 in 200 legitimate transactions.",
      "**Deployment, Monitoring, and Model Drift**\n\nFraud patterns evolve. A model trained in January 2025 will degrade by June 2025 as fraudsters adapt. Production ML fraud detection requires:\n\n**Champion-Challenger Testing** — Run the new model on 10% of traffic. Compare precision, recall, and £-value of caught fraud vs. the production model. Promote only when statistically significant.\n\n**Feature Drift Monitoring** — Track the distribution of each input feature daily. If 'foreign IP' rate jumps from 2% to 8%, it might mean your customer base changed, or it might mean a fraud campaign has started — either way, you need to know.\n\n**Feedback Loop** — Investigators must label reviewed cases within 48 hours. These labels feed the weekly retraining pipeline. Without closed-loop feedback, model accuracy degrades 15-20% over 6 months.\n\nResults from the GuardAI deployment: fraud losses reduced by 67% in year one, false positive rate reduced from 2.1% (rule-based) to 0.4% (ML), £2.3M annual saving net of system costs. The FCA compliance team cited the system's explainability layer (SHAP values per decision) as a key factor in their supervisory review.",
    ],
    relatedNichePage: "/ml/banking"
